# Code Review Checklist

Run this checklist before finishing any Python change. These are the most common issues caught in real PRs.

## PEP-8 & Naming

- [ ] All identifiers use `snake_case` — no camelCase variable, function, or class attribute names
- [ ] Pydantic model fields are `snake_case`; if JSON must be camelCase, use `alias_generator=to_camel` + `model_dump(by_alias=True)`
- [ ] Empty `__init__.py` files stay empty — no comments or docstrings
- [ ] Classes with a docstring don't have `pass` — the docstring is enough for empty bodies
- [ ] No module-level docstrings when the purpose is obvious from the file path or name

## Pydantic Models

- [ ] No `Field(...)`, `Field(title=...)`, or `Field(default=...)` wrappers — set types and defaults directly
- [ ] Only use `Field()` when you need a validator constraint or an `alias`
- [ ] `str | None` fields have a default of `= None`, not `= Field(...)` (required)

## Type Annotations

- [ ] Use `|` syntax — no `Optional[...]` or `Union[...]`
- [ ] Use built-in `list`, `dict`, `tuple` — no `List`, `Dict`, `Tuple` from `typing`

## Imports

- [ ] All imports at the top of the file — never inside functions or conditionals
- [ ] No importing `_`-prefixed symbols from another module
- [ ] No `__all__` without a strong reason — use `_` prefix for private symbols instead
- [ ] No imports in `__init__.py` unless it's the root of a library

## Error Handling

- [ ] No bare `except Exception` in route handlers — let the error-handling middleware catch it
- [ ] Use specific exception types everywhere else

## DRY / Logic

- [ ] No logic duplicated across modules — if it exists elsewhere, import it
- [ ] `__init__` only contains simple assignments — no I/O, API calls, or complex logic
- [ ] No magic strings — define a `StrEnum` or constant if applicable
- [ ] Prefer returning a small dataclass over a raw tuple from functions

## Tests

- [ ] Assert whole objects/dicts, not individual fields
- [ ] Use `@pytest.mark.parametrize` for variations — no separate test per case
- [ ] No `test_init_*` methods — refactor instead
- [ ] No standalone test files for Pydantic models — test through business logic

## Layer 1: Intent Verification (The "Why" Layer)

- [ ] Does the code match the ticket/requirement exactly?
- [ ] Are there business rules missing that only humans would know?
- [ ] Is the solution appropriately complex for the problem size?
- [ ] Would a domain expert recognize this as correct?

## Layer 2: Architecture Integration (The "How" Layer)

- [ ] Does this follow our established patterns and conventions?
- [ ] Are there existing utilities/services this should use instead?
- [ ] Does the error handling match our standard approach?
- [ ] Is the logging/monitoring consistent with our practices?
- [ ] If a folder has only one module (excluding `__init__.py`), consider inlining it into the parent folder

## Layer 3: Security & Safety (The "Risk" Layer)

- [ ] Are all inputs properly validated and sanitized?
- [ ] Does this expose any new attack surfaces?
- [ ] Are secrets/credentials handled securely?
- [ ] Does error handling avoid information leakage?

## Layer 4: Maintainability (The "Future" Layer)

- [ ] Can I understand what this code does without running it?
- [ ] Are complex algorithms commented with business justification?
- [ ] Would a new team member be able to modify this safely?
- [ ] Are there clear extension points for future requirements?

## Layer 5: Performance & Scale (The "Production" Layer)

- [ ] How does this perform with 10x our normal data volume?
- [ ] Are there obvious N+1 query patterns or similar inefficiencies?
- [ ] Does this handle timeouts and failure scenarios gracefully?
- [ ] Are resources properly cleaned up?
